    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Choosing a real estate agent is one of the most consequential decisions you will make in a property sale. The agent you appoint controls how your property is presented, how it is priced, how the campaign is run, and how offers are negotiated. A strong agent in your suburb will consistently outperform an average one, often by amounts that far exceed the difference in commission rate. Yet most sellers spend more time researching which coffee table to buy than evaluating the person who will negotiate the largest financial transaction of their lives.</p>

      <p>The appraisal meeting is a poor filter. Every experienced agent has spent years refining how to sound confident, local, and personable in a first meeting. The pitch has been rehearsed. The comparables have been selected carefully. The figure they quote you has been calibrated to what they think you want to hear. What you need is a framework for evaluating agents on data and behaviour rather than presentation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The metrics that actually tell you something</h2>
      <p>Ask every agent you meet to show you their last five comparable sales in your suburb, not their best results across their whole portfolio or across their whole career. You want recent, comparable, and local. For each of those sales, ask: what was the asking price, what did it sell for, and how many days was it on market?</p>

      <p>Days on market is a meaningful indicator. A good agent in a healthy market should be clearing well-priced properties within two to four weeks of the campaign launch. Properties sitting on market for six to ten weeks are usually the result of overpricing, poor presentation advice, or a poorly managed campaign. If an agent's recent results show a pattern of long days on market, ask them to explain it before you attribute it to market conditions.</p>

      <p>The ratio of sale price to listed price is equally informative. An agent who consistently sells at or above the asking price is either pricing accurately or managing the campaign in a way that generates genuine competition. An agent whose listings consistently sell at 5% to 8% below asking is likely overquoting at appraisal and managing expectations down during the campaign. That pattern is one of the most common complaints vendors make after a sale is done.</p>

      <p>Auction clearance rate matters if your property is likely to go to auction. Ask specifically about their clearance rate for auctions in your price range and suburb, not their overall clearance rate which may include very different property types.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The danger of choosing the highest appraisal</h2>
      <p>Overquoting to win the listing is one of the most persistent problems in the residential real estate industry. An agent who tells you your property is worth $1.4 million when the genuine market range is $1.2 to $1.25 million is not giving you a better outcome. They are giving you a higher initial expectation that they will then systematically manage down over the course of the campaign.</p>

      <p>The result for the seller is usually worse than if they had listed with an agent who priced accurately from the start. An overpriced property attracts fewer genuine buyers in the first weeks of campaign when buyer interest is highest, accumulates days on market, and often ends up selling for less than a correctly priced property would have achieved. The agent who was honest with you from the beginning was the better choice, even if the number they gave you was lower at the appraisal.</p>

      <p>A useful test: if one agent quotes significantly higher than the other two you have spoken to, ask them to show you the specific comparable sales that support that number. If they cannot, or if the comparables they show are meaningfully different from your property in size, condition, or position, be cautious.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">References: ask for three, and actually call them</h2>
      <p>Any agent worth appointing will be willing to provide references from recent sellers in your suburb. Ask for three, and make a point of actually calling them. Not emailing, calling. The conversation is more revealing than a written reference, and most people are more candid in a phone call than they are in a written testimonial.</p>

      <p>Ask each reference: how well did the agent know the suburb and the buyer pool? How often did they communicate during the campaign, and was the communication useful or just activity updates? Did the final result meet the initial expectation, and if there was a gap, how was it explained and managed? Would they use the agent again?</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The communication style test</h2>
      <p>How quickly an agent responds to your initial enquiry is a reasonable predictor of how they will communicate during your campaign. An agent who takes two days to respond to a cold enquiry from a potential seller will not suddenly become highly responsive once they have signed the Form 6. This is not a foolproof filter, but it is a real one. An agent who treats your initial contact as a priority is demonstrating the behaviour you will need from them when a buyer is sitting across the table or when an offer comes in on a Friday afternoon.</p>

      <p>During the appraisal meeting itself, pay attention to whether the agent asks you questions or does most of the talking. A good agent needs to understand your timeline, your priorities, what you need from the process, and what you are buying next. An agent who spends the whole meeting presenting rather than listening is likely to manage the campaign in the same way.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Local knowledge takes years to build</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, the suburbs within a few kilometres of each other can have significantly different buyer profiles, price drivers, and seasonal patterns. An agent who has been working Bulimba, Hawthorne, and Morningside for a decade has a buyer database, market knowledge, and network that a newer agent or an agent based in another part of the city simply cannot replicate in the short term. That local depth is worth something tangible in a campaign. Ask every agent how long they have been working in your suburb specifically, not just how long they have been in real estate generally.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Exclusive vs open listing</h2>
      <p>If you are considering listing your property with multiple agents simultaneously (an open listing), the evidence is fairly consistent: exclusive agency almost always delivers better results. An agent with exclusive authority has full incentive to invest time, effort, and marketing resources in your property, because they earn the commission regardless of which buyer they bring. An agent on an open listing knows that any of their competitors could sell the property while they are at an open home, which reduces their motivation to invest heavily in your campaign. The result is typically less effort, less buyer follow-up, and a weaker outcome for the seller.</p>

